summary: Anna Kendrick thanks doctors who treated her for kidney stones: ‘I’m so grateful’
title: Anna Kendrick thanks doctors who treated her for kidney stones: ‘I’m so grateful’
body:
Anna Kendrick has written a heartfelt note to the hospital staff who treated her for kidney stones in Atlanta, Georgia.

The Pitch Perfect actor revealed that she’d been hospitalised on Friday and penned a series of Tweets dedicated to the medical professionals who cared for her when she was at her “most vulnerable and terrified”.

“So, I need to give a shout out to the Atlanta doctors and nurses who helped me through my first experience with kidney stones,” the 33-year-old began before proceeding to name the “truly wonderful ladies” involved.

“Renee, Sandra, Muriel, Beverly, Ashley, Nina, Callie,” she wrote, confessing she couldn’t remember one person’s name.

“In fairness, you were one of the people giving me the heavy s*** right before I went under,” Kendrick added.

“But you laughed at my tired a** ‘If I die, clear my search history’ joke and I appreciate that.”

She continued: “I was worried that my pain would turn out to be ‘nothing serious’ or something that I should have been able to fight through.

…the young woman whose name started with “L”?? I can’t remember… in fairness, you were one of the people giving me the heavy shit right before I went under… but you laughed at my tired ass “If I die, clear my search history” joke and I appreciate that.

— Anna Kendrick (@AnnaKendrick47)
February 1, 2019

“I’m so grateful to these women. Even if we only interacted for a moment, know that the attention and kindness you give your patients is so appreciated.”

Kendrick’s tweets have been widely shared by her fans, with many offering messages of support and wishing her a speedy recovery.

And this is why we love you, Anna, because you aren’t too proud to thank people for what they do for you. Cheers to your healing and hoping you’re back on your feet soon! 💕

— Courtney Birkbeck (@MrsBirkbeck2010)
February 1, 2019

“Hope you’re feeling better! In your defense…im pretty sure we would all want our search histories cleared in that situation…[sic],” wrote one person.

“Anna, I feel you on so many levels,” another added.

“I had my first bout of kidney stones earlier this month while I was in the newsroom and thought it to be ‘nothing serious’ until I was in agony for four days straight… without stopping wishing for it to end. I hope your recovery goes well!”

Kidney stones are common in men and women between the ages of 30 and 60 and can be excruciatingly painful.

Symptoms vary depending on the size of the stones, but they can cause nausea, restlessness and intense pain in the back or side of your abdomen.

Most are small enough to be passed in urine, but larger stones may require surgical removal.

title: Workout program for vertical/explosiveness? via /r/Fitness
body:
I want to get back to my high school shape (23M) where I was able to dunk and have a lot more explosiveness in my jumps. Today I just feel slow. Even tho my vertical has fallen 2-3 inches it is definitely noticeable. I play rec league ball and I feel a step slower. Back in high school I did the “insanity” workout program for about 30 days to prep myself for the season. Now I’m looking for something similar that will help me get some explosiveness back? Any recommendations for programs?

aromatherapy - peppermint,...
body:
Friday, February 1st, 2019

Stress Management Techniques

tea time - peppermint, ginger, fennel ✔️

aromatherapy - peppermint, spearmint, eucalyptus blend ✔️

deep breathing/meditation ❌

stick to fucking bedtime (you God damn fool) ✔️

neck and shoulder stretches ✔️

Habits

stop picking at face ✔️

limit of two caffeinated beverages (one is green tea) ❌ 

go back to sleep after my inevitable bathroom break ✔️

journal ✔️

tidy up at least one thing/place in the house - dishes, trash, laundry, mopping ✔️

no dairy - eh does butter even count (I mean I know it does)? ✔️❌🤸

lightbox - guys, I want to use this damn thing but my husband hates it and keeps working from home ❌

Medication Taken

Zoloft, Topamax (AM+PM), Probiotic, Vitamin D, Iron/B12/Folate, Calcium, Melatonin, Multivitamin ✔️

Goals

At Least 30 Minutes of Spanish - on hiatus

Dedicated Workouts - on hiatus

Nutrition

I did a dumb. I was out and just so, so, so sleepy and getting a migraine. I hadn’t had any tea yet and I just needed caffeine. I fell onto a very old hospital past time. A Monster Zero. It really wasn’t AS bad as I thought it’d be, but it’d probably have done down much better on a full stomach. It’s not like it caused me tremendous pain. It just caused extra turbulence. I mean…it was that or a migraine. These are the situations I live with, lmao.

I took it very easy yesterday because appetite just wasn’t there. I’m starting to get those micros back up with the help of that new multivitamin, though. Y’know…assuming I’m actually absorbing that? I always take it with some fat, of course. Fun fact, you should do that, kids! About 5 grams! A, K, D, and E. Needs it! 

I did pick up some cashew butter. I needed more magnesium and calories, and that will be very easy to eat. It also has the least fiber of the nut butter so I can eat more of it without upsetting my gut. I’ll have to learn self-control, though. Me and my cashews, oh lord.

summary: How Do I Figure Out My Monthly Food Budget?
body:
How Do I Figure Out My Monthly Food Budget?

Eating healthy is more expensive than not eating healthy . Same goes for simply eating higher quality, well seasoned, and well prepared food.

I remember being broke.

I was determined to get out of credit card debt and save money for a house (which went to a wedding instead). At the time I an pretty sure that on my own, my food budget was less than $250/mo. Today, that would get you a little over 1 McDonald’s meal per day (I did a LOT of my own grocery shopping and meal prep for breakfast lunch and dinner; hmm, looking at my opening statement… Eating out all the time is more expensive than eating healthy). These days, my wife, child and I spend more than 3 times that (just realizing that I have to account for the fact that a 15 month old eats more than a 5 month old… Same goes for a 5 year old and a 15 year old… #mentalpreparation).

Anyways, it was sobering to know that as American’s we, on average, spend a smaller percentage of our income on food. 9-14% is quite the range, with 14% being one recommendation. At the same time, I have noticed, as I noticed shortly after I got out of CC debt that…

… when you have more money you tend to spend more on food.

Side note. A few months back, I realized I had saved a bit of personal spending money due to getting in the habit of delayed gratification. I started rewarding myself by following my impulses for fast food and take out.

At the same time, in addition to my growing family size, we also eat much healthier in general than I used to. It shouldn’t be a surprise, but occasionally I look at our budget and reflect back on my cheaper days. 😉

The interesting thing of looking at food spending as a percentage is that anyone, or any household can use it to see if their budget is out of sorts. E.g. my earlier budget of $250 should be supported by a monthly salary of about $1700/mo ($20K+ a year) or more to be within the 9-14% range.

Also, a percentage reminds me that it is ok to spend, or should I say invest, more on what we put in our bodies when we can afford to. In fact, it’s arguably probably one of the most important items on our monthly budget.

summary: Tough times.
title: Tough times.
body:
As awesome as this year started with news of getting more official comic book work through the year, it was soon rebalanced by the hand of karma or something and now having suffered persistent gastrointestinal trouble for over 4 weeks, I decided to go see a doctor about it as my weight has been crashing and my hands shake too much to draw most of the day. 

Unfortunately freelance artists don’t get paid in advance so the doctor fees are out of my pocket from what little I had left from last job in December and what I get from patreon, While Finland has socialized medicine, they had no free times in time frame reasonably urgent to treat me, so my only option was private sector, I’ve spent 300 euros now on that and it is not all done yet.

I haven’t got any results to post yet on what’s going on with me, which is why I have been holding off on making any announcements, as not to worry people needlessly. But i need to likely keep paying some more fees on labwork and other stuff to come so if anyone feels like tossing a little help my way you can do so via ko-fi https://ko-fi.com/pencils or paypal  paypal.me/ponysmith.

I’ll keep people posted as answers roll in.
